Is the European elite ready to trade with Britain?
The Business for Britain campaign was launched in April with the promise of bringing together businesses and defining what changes British entrepreneurs and job creation companies want to see in relation to the EU.
To this end, we commissioned the largest and most comprehensive survey, in which we asked leading British entrepreneurs for their views on Britain, trade and the EU.
YouGov surveyed 1,000 leading entrepreneurs representing UK businesses of all sizes and from different sectors and regions.
The results of the survey will come as a surprise to many.
We have found that the vast majority of companies are now trying to export outside Europe and focus on countries that are modernizing and growing, while EU countries are stagnating.
They want to see the government prioritize new trade ties with countries like China, India and Brazil rather than get bogged down in a long and arduous process of reforming the mysterious European institutions.
When asked about their views on specific policy areas - from monopoly regulation to product laws - most entrepreneurs expressed the view that control of these key competencies should return to Westminster.
There was general dissatisfaction with the single market, and entrepreneurs said that the costs of Brussels regulations now outweigh the benefits of being part of the European business area - as many as 40 percent of large companies, traditionally the most pro-European companies, agreed.
Finally, our survey of business leaders has revealed the most telling knowledge, namely that a clear majority wants Britain to work for a change in the treaty and its relationship with the EU, which should be based on trade, not politics.
The findings of companies of all sizes and major business groups show that the business sector is pushing for &quot;meaningful change&quot; that will transfer influence back to Britain.
There is a lot at stake - reaching a treaty change and a better agreement for Britain could mean up to 16% of the vote in a referendum to stay in the EU.
The Prime Minister should not hesitate: this survey shows that British trade supports his plan to amend the terms of British membership of the EU.
It also shows that the business sector expects this amendment to mean a significant shift from the current balance of power back to Britain.
A better agreement for Britain is possible and, as the eurozone embarks on a path towards closer economic and fiscal union, it is increasingly necessary.
Jobs and growth in Britain must be a priority, and as the results of our survey show, for business, this means refocusing on trade and fundamentally changing Brussels&#39; regulatory approach.
