Frontier Airlines is going to charge for hand luggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge up to $ 100 for carrying hand luggage on board on its flights.
Frontier Airlines plans to introduce a fee of up to $ 100 for hand luggage and $ 2 for coffee or soda, although they said in a statement on Wednesday that passengers would be able to keep the entire can.
The new hand luggage fee applies to luggage in the upper storage compartment, so small luggage under the seat will continue to be free.
Frontier says it will charge $ 25 if paid in advance and $ 100 if passengers wait until they arrive at the gate.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O&#39;Malley said the 100-dollar fee should encourage passengers to take care of the payment in advance.
&quot;We wouldn&#39;t like to charge this fee,&quot; she said.
Airlines started charging for the first and second checked bags in 2008.
Passengers tried to avoid these charges and stuffed their hand luggage as hidden as possible in the storage area, so there was often no space in the area.
Charges are one way of teaching passengers to take fewer things on board.
O&#39;Malley said the new fee didn&#39;t really mean to make more money.
The point is that Frontier&#39;s most loyal customers have made it very clear that it is becoming increasingly difficult to find a place in the upper storage space.
Passengers who purchase tickets on the company&#39;s website will not pay.
This means that one queued passenger at the Frontier gate can bring luggage for which he pays nothing, while the other queued passenger pays $ 100 for the same luggage.
O&#39;Malley said the website and check-in procedures will be adapted to ensure that passengers find out about the charge before they arrive at the gate.
Frontier&#39;s new hand luggage fee will not be in effect until the summer, but a date has not yet been set.
Passengers often complain about baggage fees and other charges, but airlines love them.
He claims that handling luggage costs money and that passengers who require the service should pay for it.
Many on Wall Street see the additional baggage fee as a sign that airlines are trying to raise enough money to cover the cost of air traffic after years of losses.
But most did not touch on hand luggage fees.
Spirit Airlines was the first to charge for hand luggage three years ago, and another low-cost airline, Allegiant Air, later followed suit.
The only company that also has such charges is the Hungarian Wizz Air, says air transport consultant Jay Sorensen, who is closely monitoring the additional charges.
In his December 2011 report, he estimated that Spirit&#39;s hand luggage fee would generate $ 50 million a year.
Sorensen, a former Midwest Airlines executive, recently flew with Spirit and wondered what he saw at the gate when passengers encountered an unusual Spirit baggage fee.
&quot;Getting on the plane was the smoothest I&#39;ve ever seen in my aviation career,&quot; he said.
I expected to see a gnashing of teeth and an argument at the gate.
The plane was full, he said, &quot;and the boarding took place in an instant.&quot;
Following the example of Spirit, Frontier will also charge for coffee, tea, soda and juice.
Frontier said passengers who receive lemonade or juice can keep the whole can and the coffee will be refilled for free.
Water will continue to be provided free of charge.
US Airways briefly tried to impose beverage charges in 2008, but withdrew seven months later after passenger complaints, and no other major airline imitated it.
Frontier&#39;s latest move to charge for hand luggage, unless passengers purchase a flight directly from that airline, is its last effort to direct customers directly to its website.
Airlines pay online travel retailers such as Orbitz $ 10 to $ 25 for each ticket sold.
This encouraged all airlines to buy passengers directly from them, instead of through online travel agencies.
However, Frontier went the furthest in this area.
In September, she began giving customers who bought through an online travel agency only half a mile as part of a loyalty program.
On Wednesday, she cut her reward for miles to 25 percent of the way.
So a 1000-mile trip with Frontier purchased through an online travel agency means a reward of 250 miles.
The company also allows customers to choose their seat in advance only if they make a purchase directly through the Frontier website.
Frontier has a loyal customer base in its home city of Denver, but its business is starting to shrink and lose money.
