The austerity dictated by Germany and the European Central Bank, together with the straitjacket strung on national economies through adherence to the common currency, have led many people to believe that the Europe project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments running high budget deficits - this was only true of Greece.
Rather, it is a system of the euro that blocks its members at exchange rates favorable to German exporters - and German politicians want to keep that.
Without the possibility of devaluing the domestic currency, southern Europe has a disadvantage in terms of domestic production compared to Germany.
