Behind the current budget and currency problems is a deeper cause of Europe&#39;s sluggish performance.
As a result of the &quot;green&quot; energy policy supported by Brussels - a code to support French and German companies at the expense of consumers - European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for petrol as in the United States.
This is a paralyzing disadvantage in terms of costs, as we have already seen in the case of Grangemouth.
Even any wage freeze in the world would not avert the stagnation of the European petrochemical industry with cheap shale oil from the USA.
The result is a smoldering riot, especially in France, once an ardent supporter of the EU.
After the war, the political elite in France saw the EU as a tool to keep Germany in check and allow Paris to stand up to Washington in the world.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as proof of political legitimacy and has pushed its own economic policy in Europe and left the worn-out French economy to its fate.
The result: Marine Le Pen&#39;s right wing, the anti-European National Front, had just won a major by-election and pushed the ruling Socialists to third place.
