Karel Drábek: Uhlířský vrch - one of our youngest volcanoes.
Uhlířský vrch is a striking hill 3 km southeast of Bruntál.
Together with several others, it is evidence of volcanic activity in the Low Jeseník at a time (from a geological point of view) recent.
The last eruptions were still here at the beginning of the Quaternary.
When viewed from a greater distance, on the top of Uhlířský vrch there is a striking white-plastered pilgrimage church of the Virgin Mary Help of Christians, built between 1755 and 1765.
It replaced the original wooden pilgrimage chapel.
The inn next to the church has not survived.
Shortly after the completion of the church, an alley of four rows of linden trees, about 1 km long, was planted.
The Stations of the Cross on Uhlířský vrch is already the third version, the original stood here after 1916, the second, from 2001 it lasted only until 2004.
There are wooden sculptures made by local artistic carver František Nedomlel at fifteen stops.
He used various species of woody plants from the Low Jeseník area.
Similarly, pedestals made of rocks from the local area form an interesting geological exposition.
The name of the sponsor is also given at each stop.
Uhlířský vrch is a remnant of a young volcano.
Although data from radiometric age measurements differ somewhat, the last eruption here was about 1.5 million years ago.
It is therefore younger than Velký Roudný (3.3 million years old) and older than Venus Volcano (0.8 million years old).
The volcano was born by an explosion.
During it, it expelled a considerable amount of volcanic ash, together with fragments of rocks from the subsoil, which acquired a reddish-brown color by burning.
At the end of this phase, lava flowed to the surface - today it is a layer of porous basalt up to 13 meters thick.
The second eruption ejected red, brown-red and sometimes black tuffs.
Their layer is up to 50 meters thick and part of it is accessible in the quarry wall.
Volcanic bombs up to 1 meter in size are conspicuous in the tuffs. The second eruption was also ended by a lava flow.
At the end of the activity, lava flowed out of the volcano, which today forms a layer of slag-like basalt up to 50 m thick.
Volcanoes, in which the ejection of volcanic ash alternates with lava flows, are the most common type of volcano.
Because they are actually composed of layers, they were named stratovolcanoes.
The original volcanic cone gradually eroded.
However, it was endangered by rock mining in the quarry on the south side.
The most intensive mining took place here in the years 1953 - 1962.
Tuffs were added to the concrete, which was then lighter and had better thermal insulation properties.
The mining was stopped under pressure from experts and the public, thus preserving this unique place.
However, the problem is in the porosity and low cohesion of the rocks, which quickly weather, disintegrate and slide down the slope.
The quarry disappears relatively quickly.
To make the situation even more complicated, the warm, south-facing slope is an ideal place for some rare species of plants and animals.
The remedy is therefore problematic, but over time it will be necessary to select and maintain a characteristic geological profile.
This is nothing new, similar profiles are maintained at a number of important sites.
You can get to Uhlířský vrch following the green tourist sign from Bruntál, or from Slezský Kočov.
Motorists can use the free car park at the beginning of the linden alley, where a short nature trail begins.
