The researchers shed more light on how the movements of the tail are related to the dog&#39;s mood
Previous research has shown that joyful dogs wag their tail more to the right (from the dog&#39;s point of view), while nervous dogs wave their tail mostly to the left.
However, scientists now say that other dogs can detect and respond to these subtle differences in tail movement.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neurobiologist at the University of Trento, said: &quot;It is well known in humans that the left and right sides of the brain have different links to stimuli that evoke positive or negative emotions.&quot;
We have tried to observe the same in other species.
He added that, as in humans, dogs in the right side of the brain are responsible for left-handed movements and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres play different roles in emotions.
In an effort to learn more about how dogs respond to the asymmetrical wagging of other dogs&#39; tails, researchers monitored animals that watched films about other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of these animals and analyzed their behavior.
It probably won&#39;t be long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes to one side and sometimes to the other.
Professor Vallortigara said: &quot;We have shown films about dogs to dogs - either in their natural version or in the form of a silhouette - to get rid of any confusing stimuli, and we have also been able to adjust the movement of the tail and show it more to the right or left.&quot;
When the animals saw an otherwise indistinct dog move its tail to the right (from the point of view of a dog wagging its tail), it remained completely still.
However, when she noticed the turning of the tail mostly to the left (again from the point of view of a dog wagging its tail), their heart rate increased and the animals looked uncertain.
Professor Vallortigar said that he did not think that dogs would consciously communicate with each other through these movements.
Rather, he believes that dogs have learned from experience which movements they must and which they do not have to pay attention to.
He said: &quot;If you meet dogs several times and moving their tail in one direction is repeatedly associated with more friendly behavior and moving to the right produces less friendly behavior, you will respond based on this experience.&quot;
Researchers say the findings can help dog owners, veterinarians and trainers better understand the emotions of their animals.
Dog behavior expert John Bradshaw, a college veterinary teacher at the University of Bristol, said it was not the first study to look at whether the left and right sides were important to dogs.
Last year, a team from Lincoln University found that dogs turn their heads to the left when watching an aggressive dog, and to the right when looking at a cheerful dog.
And in another dissertation from the University of Victoria in Canada, he said: &quot;Dogs were more likely to get acquainted with a dog robot when it wagged its tail to the left than to the right, when they became more insecure - quite the opposite of the Italian study.&quot;
According to him, the difference may be given by the fact that dogs in these various studies did not interpret animals in movies or dog robots completely like dogs.
He explained that a study on how dogs respond to real dogs could help.
&quot;Although there is strong evidence for many different mammals that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be clarified - and dogs are no exception,&quot; he said.
But given how easy it is to record their behavior, it probably won&#39;t be long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes to one side and sometimes to the other.
