FAA: Air passengers can now use technology advances on airplanes (but not call from their cell phones)
Airline passengers will be able to use their electronic devices &quot;gate to gate&quot; - in addition to calling from their mobile phones - to read, play games, watch movies and listen to music under the eagerly awaited new rules issued by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) on Thursday. ).
But passengers should not expect changes to happen immediately.
How quickly the change will be implemented will vary from airline to airline, FAA Administrator Michael Huerta told a news conference.
Airlines will need to demonstrate to the FAA Administration to the extent that their aircraft comply with the new rules and that they have updated flight crew training manuals and stowage guidelines to comply with the new rules.
The FAA said it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices in aircraft.
Delta and JetBlue are among the companies that have already handed over the plans.
&quot;Depending on the status of such a plan, we can improve the widespread use of electronic devices very quickly,&quot; the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers are required to turn off their smartphones, tablets and other devices as soon as the aircraft doors are closed.
They cannot turn them on until the aircraft reaches a height of 3 kilometers and the captain issues a permit.
Passengers are expected to turn off their devices again when the aircraft descends to land and do not turn them on until the aircraft is on the ground.
Under the new rules, airlines whose aircraft are properly protected against electronic interference can allow their passengers to use their equipment during takeoff, landing and taxiing, the FAA said.
Most new commercial aircraft and other aircraft that have been modified to allow passengers to use Wifi at higher altitudes are expected to meet these criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the Association of Professional Stewards, welcomed the changes.
&quot;Once the new rules are safely implemented - and we will work closely with transport companies - it will be a success,&quot; Glading said in a statement.
Honestly, we are tired of looking like &quot;watchdogs&quot;.
However, surfing the Internet, sending e-mails and sms or downloading data will continue to be prohibited below 3 kilometers above sea level, the agency said.
Passengers will be notified to switch their smartphones, tablets and other devices to air mode.
So still no Words with friends, an online scrabble game played by actor Alec Baldwin on his smartphone in 2011 when, as is well known, he was thrown off an American Airlines plane because he refused to turn off his device when the plane was parked at the gate.
And heavier devices like laptops will still have to be stored for fear that they could injure someone if they flew around the cabin.
Calls from mobile phones will continue to be prohibited on board.
The rules for the use of mobile phones are not determined by the FAA, but by the US Federal Telecommunications Committee.
The FAA may lift the ban on some electronic devices during takeoff and landing.
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the State Committee on Transportation Safety, a national transport safety expert at CBS News, said cell phones continue to be considered a risk.
&quot;Mobile phones are really a problem, not only because they can potentially create interference with navigation devices, but we also know from FCC data that they can cause interference to broadcast towers in the air,&quot; said Rosenker.
A sectoral advisory committee set up by the FAA administration to investigate the issue last month suggested that the government allow the wider use of electronic devices.
The FAA has been pressured in recent years to ease restrictions on their use.
Critics such as Senator Claire McCaskill, a Missouri Democrat, argue that there is no valid security reason for the ban.
Restrictions are also becoming increasingly difficult to enforce, as the use of such devices is ubiquitous.
Some studies suggest that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore the obligation to switch off their facilities.
The FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices by passengers in 1966 in response to the disruption of navigation and communications equipment when passengers began carrying FM radios, a technical achievement of the time.
New airlines are much more dependent on electrical systems than previous-generation aircraft, but they are also designed and approved by the FAA to be resistant to electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering passengers the use of Wi-Fi at cruising altitudes for several years.
Plans adapted for Wi-Fi systems are also more resistant to interference.
The vast majority of airlines should adapt to greater use of electronic devices under the new rules, Huert said.
Today&#39;s electronic devices generally emit much less intense radio transmissions than previous generations.
For example, e-readers emit only minimal transmissions when turning a page.
But transmission is stronger when devices download or send data.
Among those pushing for restrictions on the use of these devices by passengers is Amazon.com.
In 2011, representatives of the company loaded the airliner with their Kindle electronic readers and performed a test flight, but no problem appeared.
Members of the FAA Advisory Committee have expressed mixed feelings about whether these facilities pose any risks.
Douglas Kidd of the National Airline Passenger Association said he believed the interference from these facilities was real, even when the risk was minimal.
Other members of the committee said that there were only sketchy reports from pilots to support the fact that such devices could cause disruption to aircraft systems, and most of these reports were very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to instruct passengers to turn off equipment while flying under low-visibility instruments.
The travel industry group welcomed these changes and said it was a sensible practice for the traveling public to make extensive use of technology.
&quot;We are pleased that the FAA has recognized that a pleasant travel experience is not in conflict with safety,&quot; said Roger Dow, executive director of the American Travel Association.
