Obstruction policy cannot excuse the plight of Obama&#39;s health care website or drone attacks
Memoirs of Obama&#39;s 2008 campaign are a sad reminder of what might have happened
Nathaniel P. Morris is studying medicine at Harvard for the second year.
These days I&#39;m reading a very sad book.
I thought of this book that during the gloomy days of my sophomore year at medical school, I would be encouraged and renewed by a pinch of hope.
It&#39;s called &quot;The Audacity to Win&quot; and is a recollection of Barack Obama&#39;s presidential campaign in 2008.
When I finish the patient reviews in the evening and go to bed, the book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions of people and the speeches took your breath away.
The election ended in overwhelming dominance, and television news forced us to reflect on the historical value of the moment.
My classmates cried with joy and my parents hid the newspaper they got.
A young team of visionaries headed for the White House and the nation was ready for change.
During his inauguration in 2008, Obama had 82 percent support.
And here I close the book.
Going to the present is a harsh awakening, like waking up from a dream.
It&#39;s hard to remember these optimistic days - they seem like distant memories, a sad reminder of missed opportunities.
In the years since I dropped my first ballot, there have indeed been changes.
It was definitely not anything I imagined.
I acknowledge that Obama has achieved a number of great and varied successes - from the law on affordable care to the expulsion of our troops from Iraq and the end of the &quot;ask nothing, say nothing&quot; policy after the death of Osama bin Laden.
In addition, I believe that the party&#39;s obstruction has turned so many efforts to move our nation forward: it is, among other things, immigration reform, the possibility for the public to choose health care and the closure of the Guantánamo base.
But after many situations of defending the Obama administration from colleagues and friends, I have reached an absolute limit as to the explanations they can provide.
I found myself in a place of political despair.
Republican obstruction cannot explain consent to the wiretapping of foreign leaders or the raids of drones that kill innocent children overseas.
They cannot explain the fact that the National Security Agency collects data about the private lives of Americans, nor that it persecutes those who expose government misconduct.
They cannot be held responsible for the execution of Anwar al-Awlaki, an American citizen, without due process or for limiting public contributions and expenses during presidential campaigns.
They cannot justify finding a report that says the White House&#39;s efforts to silence the media are &quot;the most aggressive ... since the Nixon administration.&quot;
And most recently, they can&#39;t even excuse the inability to create a simple website more than 3 years after signing the Affordable Care Act.
I don&#39;t know if something like that was to be expected.
Whether I should have known at the age of 18 that government power might be at odds with the political campaigns that preceded it.
The elected office is clearly unpredictable, and our public talks will be shaped by opposition political parties and random events such as the Newton massacre.
However, all the examples I have given above seem to be largely the result of the administration&#39;s own decision.
And that bothers me the most.
I re-elected Obama in 2012, but not because I was thrilled with his candidacy.
Mitt Romney was a confusing and unsolved alternative and seemed unable to consolidate his policy or position.
I felt that the second term for Obama, free from the pressure of the next election, would fulfill the hopes we had once heard about.
Still, going back to 2008 - with Obama&#39;s support falling below 45% this week - through this book is getting harder.
It makes me remember the many promises that have disappeared.
This week, I read a chapter in the book about how Obama suffered a crushing defeat with Clinton during the Pennsylvania primaries.
At an additional meeting during the campaign, he told his staff that he needed to get back on track and stay true to his mission.
&quot;I want our magic back,&quot; he said.
We must not forget who we are.
Five years have passed, Mr President, and I completely agree with you.
The ideas expressed in this commentary are solely those of Nathaniel Morris.
