Early puberty: Mature earlier
Research has shown that African American and Hispanic women reach puberty earlier than their white peers.
Physical changes do not mean that puberty is approaching
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are behind it
Experts say that an obesity epidemic may be one of the triggers of earlier puberty.
The trend of earlier puberty is not so noticeable in boys.
Former CNN reporter Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in children&#39;s health and family issues.
Should a mother be horrified when her daughter&#39;s breasts and pubic hair begin to grow at the age of 7 or 8?
At the American Academy of Pediatricians&#39; annual conference in Orlando, Florida this week, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these physical changes are relatively common among American girls and set a new standard.
&quot;I&#39;ve spent a lot of time reassuring my parents that it&#39;s usually not a sign of rapid development toward full puberty,&quot; Kaplowitz said.
Visible signs of development, such as breast growth, pubic and armpit hair, and body odor, appear earlier in girls.
Over the last forty years, however, there has been little change in the age at which menstruation occurs.
In the United States, the average age is now 12.5, compared with 12.75 in 1970.
&quot;When breasts begin to develop, it takes at least two to three years for the first period,&quot; said Kaplowitz, who is also the author of &quot;Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to Coping with This Common Problem.&quot; : An essential guide to dealing with this common problem)
The most reliable test of how puberty will continue is time.
What activates the true onset of puberty is discussed, but if breast growth is accompanied by growth spurt before the age of 8, the girl is considered &quot;prematurely mature.&quot;
In most cases, the process slows down or stops - which pediatricians can closely monitor.
Faster growth may be the reason for the endocrinologist to perform tests to rule out serious problems such as a tumor or cyst.
There are treatments that delay early menstruation and prevent other consequences: premature bone aging, which can eventually lead to stunted growth and stunting in adulthood.
Recommendations regarding medications and hormonal treatment depend on the child&#39;s age, rate of development, growth rate and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is cautious about taking drugs, but acknowledges that &quot;suppressing puberty can alleviate a girl&#39;s behavioral problems and feelings that are different from her peers.&quot;
Another big problem is understandable: Parents simply do not want their very young daughters to be menstruating.
&quot;They&#39;re worried she might get pregnant, or how she&#39;s going to handle hygiene,&quot; Kaplowitz said.
&quot;It was a shock,&quot; recalls a woman whose daughter began menstruating at the age of 10.
Although there were signs and talks about menstruation, she was not emotionally prepared.
She came home from school scared and upset that she was the first of her friends.
There are many well-known theories about the causes of premature puberty.
However, there is still no coherent body of evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, environmental chemicals, or sexual messages in the media are to blame.
Boys - like girls - reach puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz argues that the most serious reason is the obesity epidemic.
In 2001, he helped carry out a study on girls aged 6 to 9, which linked body fat to the timing of puberty.
Other findings support this conclusion, but there are many other contributing factors.
In this country, African American and Hispanic women tend to reach puberty earlier than their white counterparts.
The explanations are different.
From a global perspective, patterns of early puberty appear to be influenced by everything from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another riddle: Although boys develop facial and pubic hair at an early age, the trend toward full bloom of early puberty is not as clear as that of girls.
Other physicians attending the American Pediatric Association (AAP) conference added additional complexity to this topic.
Acne and pubic hair are common even in infants and toddlers.
&quot;We need to be careful about how we identify the true onset of puberty,&quot; said Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Goryeb Children&#39;s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to get instructions from their pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
&quot;It may mean having to talk to your child sooner than you think,&quot; Kaplowitz advised.
If you stay calm, your child is likely to respond well.
Girls who develop earlier need reassurance that even if it happens prematurely, this process is a normal part of life.
