Bombardier&#39;s profit fell due to declining supplies and orders
Canadian aircraft and train manufacturer Bombardier reported a 15 percent drop in net profit on Thursday, due to fewer aircraft orders and deliveries in the third quarter and contractual problems in the train unit.
Montreal-based Bombardier has also not released any flight test data for its new CSeries aircraft, nor has it provided up-to-date information on whether the aircraft will adhere to an ambitious plan to begin commercial operations from next September.
After the initial test flight about a month and a half ago, the aircraft flew only three times, and the question arose as to whether the test phase was progressing well.
The results did not meet estimates and shares on the Toronto Stock Exchange fell by 8 percent.
State bank analyst Cameron Doerksen downgraded from &quot;higher returns&quot; to &quot;sector performance&quot; on Thursday, with the expectation that the stock market will experience limited growth over the next quarter or two.
&quot;While we mostly expected smaller aircraft deliveries, we were significantly disappointed by the transport profit margin,&quot; Doerksen told clients.
As the trial continues, we hope Bombardier will win new orders for CSeries aircraft.
However, if no new orders are announced in the coming months, we expect market skepticism about this program to increase.
Bombardier hopes that CSeries aircraft will make their way to the bottom of the market, which is now dominated by Boeing and Airbus.
The first test aircraft was unveiled in March, and after a delay of several months, the first flight took place in September.
However, the number of binding orders for CSeries aircraft is a modest 177, as potential buyers are waiting for the results of a test flight to be able to verify the company&#39;s claims regarding the low consumption and cost savings of this airliner.
At present, there are a total of 403 orders and commitments from 15 customers and operators.
CEO Pierre Beaudoin expected Bombardier to reach its target of 300 binding orders when the first aircraft were put into commercial use.
Executives also assured analysts and the media on Thursday that the program was progressing according to plan.
&quot;The test aircraft did not stay on the ground longer than expected,&quot; Beaudoin said in a conference call, noting that ground tests and software updates were scheduled during the outage.
Every manufacturer plans them differently.
We decided to go through the first flight and then focus on the updates and we did.
This will happen throughout the flight program.
According to Bombardier, the second of five test planes should take off in the coming weeks and the others shortly thereafter.
However, analysts are skeptical that the first customer could start operating a CSeries aircraft 12 months after its first flight.
Bombardier claims that it has evaluated its plan for putting the aircraft into operation and will provide updated information in the coming months.
&quot;This slow pace of flight testing - while in line with Bombardier&#39;s internal plan - is likely to reinforce our view that commissioning will be postponed to the first quarter of 2015,&quot; said Doerksen.
From $ 172 million, or 9 cents a share, a year earlier, Bombardier&#39;s net income fell to $ 147 million, or 8 cents a share, in the third quarter ended September 30.
Adjusted earnings per share remained unchanged at 9 cents.
Turnover fell marginally from $ 4.2 billion to $ 4.1 billion.
According to Thomson Reuters&#39; IBES system, analysts expected a yield of 10 cents per share and a turnover of 4.56 billion.
The fourth largest aircraft manufacturer stated that, compared to 57 aircraft a year earlier, it had supplied only 45 aircraft during the quarter.
Net orders fell from 83 aircraft to 26.
Outstanding orders in the aviation division amounted to 32.9 billion as of September 30, which does not change as of December 31.
&quot;The results in aviation were in line with our outlook, but low order intake and the overall state of the market disappointed us,&quot; said Beaudoin.
Revenue in the aerospace industry fell 13 percent to $ 2 billion.
Bombardier, the world&#39;s largest train maker, said revenue in the division rose nearly 11 percent to $ 2.1 billion.
Outstanding orders in transport amounted to 32.6 billion as of September 30, which is a marginal increase compared to December 31.
The profit margin in the transport division was affected by problems with the implementation of several large contracts.
Executives said new prospects would be provided in the fourth quarter.
Shares of Bombardier, which also announced the arrival of Google CFO Patrick Pichette, fell 8.5 percent to $ 4.83 during trading on Thursday afternoon.
Brazil&#39;s Embraer SA, Bombardier&#39;s third-largest commercial aircraft manufacturer and closest competitor, announced a 10 percent drop in quarterly earnings on Thursday.
