The bill comes amid a series of measures to strengthen national security in the wake of the September attack by an Islamic gunman in the Westgate Mall.
The Kenyan media turned the anger of the authorities when it broadcast a security camera recording of soldiers sent to the scene of the attack, allegedly looting a luxury goods store.
The police chief responded by having two journalists and a senior media officer summoned for questioning, but the summons was later withdrawn after pressure from the media.
Under the new bill, media companies may be fined up to 20 million Kenyan shillings and individual journalists up to one million, along with the risk of being &quot;de-listed&quot; or denied official journalist accreditation.
The tribunal also has the right to seize the offender&#39;s property if the fine is not paid.
